---
import '../../styles/global.css';
import LessonLayout from '../../layouts/LessonLayout.astro';
import LessonHeader from '../../components/LessonHeader.astro';
import LessonNav from '../../components/LessonNav.astro';
import InsightBox from '../../components/InsightBox.astro';
import TagBadge from '../../components/TagBadge.astro';
import SnapLevelsDemo from '../../components/demos/SnapLevelsDemo.astro';
---

<LessonLayout title="Fewer bits, on purpose" lessonNumber="0.1" section="The trade-off">

    <LessonHeader lessonNumber="0.1" title="Fewer bits, on purpose" description="Quantization is rounding with intent: keep only a few allowed levels, and snap every value to the nearest one.">
        <TagBadge variant="concepts">concepts</TagBadge>
        <TagBadge variant="default">8 min read</TagBadge>
    </LessonHeader>

    <section class="mb-14">
        <h2 class="text-xl font-bold mb-4">You already do this</h2>
        <p class="text-mt-muted leading-relaxed mb-4">
            Ask someone the time and they say "quarter past," not "thirteen minutes and forty seconds past."
            They round to a small set of allowed answers because it is close enough and far easier to carry.
            Write 3.14 instead of 3.14159 and you have done the same thing: thrown away detail you did not
            need, to save space.
        </p>
        <p class="text-mt-muted leading-relaxed mb-4">
            That is all quantization is. Pick a handful of allowed values, the <strong>levels</strong>, and
            store each real number as the nearest level. Drag the value below and watch it snap. Then change
            how many levels there are.
        </p>

        <SnapLevelsDemo />

        <InsightBox>
            <p class="text-sm">Quantization replaces a continuous value with the nearest of a fixed set of
            <strong>levels</strong>. The gap between the real value and the stored level is the
            <strong>quantization error</strong>.</p>
        </InsightBox>
    </section>

    <section class="mb-14">
        <h2 class="text-xl font-bold mb-4">More levels, less error</h2>
        <p class="text-mt-muted leading-relaxed mb-4">
            With only 4 levels spread across 0 to 10, the value 6.5 has nowhere exact to land. The nearest
            level is about 6.7, so you store 6.7 and accept an error of 0.2. Add more levels and the nearest
            one sits closer, so the error shrinks. The demo makes this concrete: 2 levels are coarse, 16 are
            fine.
        </p>
        <div class="bg-white border border-mt-border rounded-xl p-5 mb-4 font-mono text-sm leading-relaxed">
            value 6.5, 4 levels &nbsp;&rarr;&nbsp; nearest 6.7, error 0.2<br />
            value 6.5, 16 levels &nbsp;&rarr;&nbsp; nearest 6.5, error 0.0
        </div>
        <p class="text-mt-muted leading-relaxed">
            The catch is that more levels cost more space to write down, which is the whole trade-off and the
            subject of the next lesson.
        </p>
    </section>

    <section class="mb-14">
        <h2 class="text-xl font-bold mb-4">Levels are counted in bits</h2>
        <p class="text-mt-muted leading-relaxed mb-4">
            How much space a level costs is measured in <strong>bits</strong>. With one bit you can name 2
            levels, with two bits 4, with three bits 8. In general, b bits name 2 to the power b levels. The
            number you will meet most often is 8 bits, one <strong>byte</strong>, which names 256 levels.
            That is the size of a single number after the simplest quantizer in this course.
        </p>
        <div class="bg-white border border-mt-border rounded-xl p-5 font-mono text-sm leading-relaxed">
            1 bit &rarr; 2 levels &nbsp;&middot;&nbsp; 2 bits &rarr; 4 &nbsp;&middot;&nbsp; 4 bits &rarr; 16
            &nbsp;&middot;&nbsp; 8 bits &rarr; 256
        </div>
    </section>

    <section class="mb-14">
        <h2 class="text-xl font-bold mb-4">Key takeaways</h2>
        <div class="space-y-3">
            <div class="flex items-start gap-3"><div class="w-6 h-6 rounded-full bg-mt-accentLight flex items-center justify-center flex-shrink-0 mt-0.5"><span class="text-mt-accent font-bold text-xs">1</span></div><p class="text-sm">Quantization snaps each value to the nearest of a fixed set of levels. The leftover gap is the quantization error.</p></div>
            <div class="flex items-start gap-3"><div class="w-6 h-6 rounded-full bg-mt-accentLight flex items-center justify-center flex-shrink-0 mt-0.5"><span class="text-mt-accent font-bold text-xs">2</span></div><p class="text-sm">More levels mean smaller error, because the nearest level sits closer to the true value.</p></div>
            <div class="flex items-start gap-3"><div class="w-6 h-6 rounded-full bg-mt-accentLight flex items-center justify-center flex-shrink-0 mt-0.5"><span class="text-mt-accent font-bold text-xs">3</span></div><p class="text-sm">Levels are paid for in bits: b bits buy 2^b levels, and 8 bits (one byte) buy 256.</p></div>
        </div>
    </section>

    <LessonNav
        prevHref="/learn" prevLabel="Course map"
        nextHref="/foundations/memory-vs-accuracy" nextLabel="Next: Memory vs accuracy"
    />

</LessonLayout>
